positive.review:
Show those fucking clankers who's boss and why God created man and not machine.

In the end I enjoyed this game despite quite a lot of ... strange if not bad things/design decisions, and some really annoying bugs.

The meat and potatoes of this game is a kind of dumbed down Bioshock with more focus on guns than skills/magic, or Prey (the 2017 game) with a bit better gunplay.

Many other reviewers are trying to compare this game to Fallout but it has nothing to do with Fallout except the time frame which is some time in the 1950s but the style is completely different and it's just a different type of game and atmosphere.

What I liked:
- destroying endless mobs of stupid clankers and some zombie things;
- cool guns which you can modify;
- the main plot was kind of interesting, at least it made me want to see what happens next;
- some parts of the dialogue were kind of funny;
- graphics are pretty good (but not to the point where it justifies how the game runs ... see below).

What I didn't like:

Relatively minor things which I could look over:
- some parts of the story and dialogue are pretty campy - the main character is oscillating between russian Duke Nukem and wholesome mc smarty-pants which is just weird. They should have just gone for one or the other. Towards the end of the game it gets a bit better but most people who don't like this won't get that far;
- enemy variety could be a bit better - towards the end the game does get a bit repetitive;
- the MC and guns get to be too overpowered by the end of the game, even at higher difficulties - bosses end up being a joke - even the end boss was not a challenge at all, and I didn't even use a lot of the buffs like vodka and condensed milk (da, comrade, that is a thing);
- the "magic" skills you have are not that varied , wish there would be some more stuff there;
- the melee weapons are very same-y and don't feel so different - I just used a single one through the entire playthrough;
- even on latest 2025 hardware the game has areas where it runs poorly (albeit on 4k with RayTracing activated, and DLSS on balanced, but still) and in general the way it looks does not justify how much power it requires;

Super annoying things which almost made me not recommend:

- there are still a lot of bugs related to map geometry which means your character can easily get stuck in places where you can't get out of, or you trip over invisible things when trying to charge at enemies or trying to escape;

- some quests require you to manipulate physics objects which sometimes bug out and you can't manipulate them anymore - had to reload a save a couple of times because of this;

- there is a lot of platforming in this game but in places where clearly you can easily jump/vault over something or grab onto something, your character can't do it because the devs decided that's not allowed - yet 5 meters to the right may be a thing which is even bigger or taller than what you just tried and is perfectly vaultable because random ... this is really annoying when navigating the open world and trying to escape from enemies or reach loot boxes or something like that;

- some platforming puzzles require you to make relatively precise jumps which the game's physics engine tries to make you fail - e.g. if you run too fast into a wall you will kind of "bump" away from it, which is a bit realistic I guess but is super ultra annoying when trying to solve some of these puzzles . Also sometimes your MC just doesn't grab onto clearly grabbable ledges from the firs time, or misses jumps even though you smash that stupid space bar into oblivion - crispy critters!!!

In the end I did still have fun, and I could get past the campy story and graphics slowdowns but I almost , almost , had the experience ruined by all these mentioned bugs.
